      "\n    -- Now we need to show that the inits are equal\n    -- Let's think about the structure\n```\n\nAfter the induction hypothesis `ih`, we need to prove the equality for `x :: xs`.\n\nLet's compute both sides:\n\n- `inits₁ (x :: xs)`:\n  - `reverse (x :: xs)` is `(x :: xs).reverse = [x] ++ (xs.reverse)` (wait, actually `reverse (x :: xs)` is `xs.reverse ++ [x]`)\n  - `tails (reverse (x :: xs))` is `tails (xs.reverse ++ [x])`\n  - `map reverse (tails (reverse (x :: xs)))` is `map reverse (tails (xs.reverse ++ [x]))`\n\n- `inits₂ (x :: xs)`:\n  - `List.map (fun y ↦ y.reverse) (List.reverse (List.tails (List.reverse (x :: xs))))`\n  - This is `List.map reverse (tails (reverse (x :: xs)))` which is the same as `inits₁ (x :: xs)`\n\nWait, actually, `inits₁` is defined as `map reverse ∘ reverse ∘ tails ∘ reverse`. So:\n\n`inits₁ (x :: xs)` = `map reverse (reverse (tails (reverse (x :: xs))))`\n= `map reverse (reverse (tails (xs.reverse ++ [x])))`\n= `map reverse (reverse ( (xs.reverse ++ [x]).tails ))`\n= `map reverse ( ( (xs.reverse ++ [x]).tails ).reverse )`\n= `map reverse ( [ reverse each suffix of (xs.reverse ++ [x]) ] )`\n= `map reverse ( [ reverse (xs.reverse ++ [x]), reverse (xs.reverse ++ [x]).tail, ... ] )`\n= `[ reverse (reverse (xs.reverse ++ [x]) ), reverse (reverse (xs.reverse ++ [x]).tail ), ... ]`\n= `[ (xs.reverse ++ [x]), (xs.reverse ++ [x]).tail, ... ]` (since `reverse reverse = id`)\n= `inits (xs.reverse ++ [x])`\n\nBut `inits (xs.reverse ++ [x])` is the list of all prefixes of `xs.reverse ++ [x]`.\n\nWait, this is getting confusing. Let's try to compute directly.\n\nAlternatively, we can try to compute both sides explicitly for a small example.\n\nLet's take `xs = [1, 2, 3]`.\n\nThen `inits₁ [1, 2, 3]`:\n- `reverse [1, 2, 3]` = `[3, 2, 1]`\n- `tails [3, 2, 1]` = `[[3, 2, 1], [2, 1], [1], []]`\n- `map reverse` on this: `[[3, 2, 1].reverse, [2, 1].reverse, [1].reverse, [ ].reverse]` = `[[1, 2, 3], [1, 2], [1], []]`\n\n`inits₂ [1, 2, 3]`:\n- `L